---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Teaching · Carey Manwa"
  description="Teaching at Cornell: ORIE 3120 course assistant and Bowers CIS TA for ~300 students a semester, with perfect 10/10 evaluations across three consecutive semesters."
>
  <div class="col">
    <header class="article-header">
      <span class="eyebrow">Teaching<span class="dot">·</span>Cornell University</span>
      <h1>Teaching</h1>
      <p class="abstract">
        I teach the tools I use to do research, and I take the craft of
        explaining as seriously as the craft of building.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="stat-row reveal">
      <div class="stat">
        <span class="num">10/10</span>
        <span class="label">evaluation score</span>
      </div>
      <div class="stat">
        <span class="num">×3</span>
        <span class="label">consecutive semesters</span>
      </div>
      <div class="stat">
        <span class="num">~300</span>
        <span class="label">students / semester</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <section class="reveal">
      <h2 style="font-size: var(--text-lg); margin-top: var(--space-6);">
        Course Assistant · ORIE 3120
      </h2>
      <span class="eyebrow">OR, MACHINE LEARNING &amp; DATA SCIENCE</span>
      <p>
        Cornell's applied data science core for engineers. I support students
        across the full stack of the course: SQL and Python for data work,
        Tableau for communication, and the modeling sequence of regression,
        classification, time-series forecasting, and A/B testing. The course's
        center of gravity is judgment: knowing which method answers which
        question.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="reveal">
      <h2 style="font-size: var(--text-lg); margin-top: var(--space-6);">
        Teaching Assistant · Cornell Bowers CIS
      </h2>
      <span class="eyebrow">INTRO TO DATA SCIENCE · INTRO TO WEB DEVELOPMENT</span>
      <p>
        Roughly 300 students a semester, most writing their first real code.
        Across three consecutive semesters of doing this, my student
        evaluations came back a perfect 10/10 each time.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="reveal">
      <h2 style="font-size: var(--text-lg); margin-top: var(--space-6);">
        How I teach
      </h2>
      <p>
        The same way I write software: start from the failure case. Students
        don't learn debugging from slides; they learn it the moment their own
        code breaks and someone shows them how to read the error instead of
        fearing it. My office hours optimize for that moment. I'd rather a
        student leave knowing how to get unstuck than leave with their
        assignment finished.
      </p>
      <p>
        Before Cornell, I led 20 mentors at EducationUSA reaching 20,000+
        students across 30 Kenyan high schools. That was teaching at a very different
        scale, with the same conviction:
        <a href="/about/">access to knowledge is a distribution problem, and
        distribution problems are solvable</a>.
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
